data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — these APIs work identically in modern .NET and will compile and run correctly on .NET 8 as-is.

There are no references to `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt` in this code.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort migration): you could replace the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` for cleaner code, e.g.:

```csharp
Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
{
    Thread.Sleep(100);
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
});
```

But this is purely a style/convenience improvement — your existing code is already .NET 8–compatible.
